When I was a kid, probably around 4-5, Mum and I were on a walk in the bush near our house. The fact that Mum doesn't remember makes me think it's a fake memory but I have such a vivid image of petting the snake, and Mum's face when she saw me. Really creeps me out.

You probably hear this a lot, but it's important to study smarter, not harder. In my first years of uni I would spend hours writing pages and pages of copied notes just to try and retain the information long enough to pass an exam, but now I find it so much easier and more effective studying other ways. For example, I try to figure out exactly what I need to know, and then work out how much of this I already know and how much I don't. Once I figure out what I don't know, I mentally create questions to find answers to in my own way so I'll actually fully learn and understand the answer. It's a good idea to use a lot of resources (e.g. textbooks by professionals in your field alongside your uni lectures/notes and trustworthy websites/articles) to get a deeper understanding of the content and see different perspectives. Basically the thing that's made the biggest difference for me is just not writing down literally everything (including things I already know and things I don't fully understand) and just focusing on what I don't know. If there's things you can't figure out, make a note of it and ask someone.
